# Boring Zone!

This part is just oversharing unimportant stuff.

## My Journey From Beginning 

I started learning using computers before I could even read. My father taught me how to play "Age of Empires" when I was really young. I continued using them like any other kid, and I started learning about programming around my 4th grade.

At that stage, I had a dream of "making games". My father tried to teach me fundamentals of QBasic, so he did.
I stopped learning QBasic, in favor of Visual Basic. Isn't that great? Ancient languages? At the time, I was 12.

By then, I got a gift from my family: a "Unity Tutorial" CD. I tried to learn about it, but failed because I didn't know C#.

That was when I searched for a C# course in my hometown, and I couldn't find one. So what did I do? I booked a class I _could_ find; PHP/HTML/CSS/JS. I went there for 12 sessions, and after that, I completely switched to online learning through W3School translations and documentations.

### High-school Era

I was a "web boy" during my middle school era, but in the middle of my 9th grade, I made a challenge for myself: learn about how computers can possibly talk.
I asked in a few forums, and found out that Andrew Ng's ML course on Coursera is almost the perfect entry point. So I audited his course, and started watching it.

A boy my age did know about derivatives and line equation, but he didn't know ANYTHING about linear regression, linear algebra or anything like that.
Fortunately, I had my father and mother supporting me, and I appreciate their existence to this day.

So, what did I do? Give up? **Never**. My father bought me a few books: "Linear Algebra: O'Nan, Michael", and 3 "Numerical Analysis & Methods" books for interpolation, regression and so.
I stopped programming for a while, and studied what my dad gave me.
I studied what my dad gave me to study, I learned about Gaussian Elimination, linear independence, and so on, implemented them in GNU Octave! Good ol' days.
Then, for high school, I chose "Natural Sciences" over "Math", and I studied biology university books for "Biology Olympiad". I had spent a lot of time on biology I had little time for programming.
But fortunately, the map overlapped with what I was studying heavily. Biology Olympiad, unlike its name, is math heavy in Iran. It had:
- Differential equations (for Ecology),
- Combinatorics and Discrete Math (for Classical Genetics)
- Statistics and Regression (for Statistics of populations, etc.)

I studied a lot of biology books, ranging from "Guyton's Medical Physiology" to "Simpson's Plant Systematics". That's still my hobby. I like biology very much.

In parallel, I sometimes continued Andrew Ng's Deep Learning course when I found some free time.


### Back to Computers!

In the last year on my high-school, I had a sudden change of heart: I liked biology, but I didn't want to be a doctor.
So I changed my major to "Math & Physics" for my last year, and then, was accepted in CSE in Shiraz University (for your reference, in Iran, CSE is more popular than CS).

---

Hope you'll enjoy my website!
